      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The eugenics movement of the early 1900s relied heavily on pseudoscientific theories, such as Social Darwinism and craniometry, to justify their claims of racial superiority. They argued that certain \"races\" were inherently more intelligent, capable, or desirable, and that interbreeding between these \"superior\" and \"inferior\" groups would inevitably lead to the degradation of the latter. They also claimed that \"undesirable\" traits, such as poverty, crime, and mental illness, were inherited and could be eliminated through selective breeding or sterilization. These arguments were often based on flawed scientific theories and were used to justify discriminatory policies and practices.",
